# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: standard-cell-library
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] A **gate equivalent** (**GE**) stands for a unit of measure which allows specifying *manufacturing-technology-independent complexity* of digital electronic circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] For today's CMOS technologies, the silicon area of a two-input drive-strength-one NAND gate usually constitutes the *technology-dependent* unit area commonly referred to as gate equivalent.
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] A specification in gate equivalents for a certain circuit reflects a complexity measure, from which a corresponding silicon area can be deduced for a dedicated manufacturing technology.
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] In digital circuit design, a dedicated *standard cell library* is employed for each manufacturing technology (e.g., CMOS).
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] The standard cell library comprises many different logic gates, for example a NAND gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] For each logical type of logic gate, e.g., a two-input NAND, there usually exist different physical realizations in the standard cell library, for instance with different output drive strengths.
[src:standard-cell-library/gate-equivalent] Basically, a two-input drive-strength-one NAND gate in CMOS technology consists of four transistors.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A **logic gate** is a device that performs a Boolean function, a logical operation performed on one or more binary inputs that produces a single binary output.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Depending on the context, the term may refer to an **ideal logic gate**, one that has, for instance, zero rise time and unlimited fan-out, or it may refer to a non-ideal physical device (see ideal and real op-amps for comparison).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The primary way of building logic gates uses diodes or transistors acting as electronic switches.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Today, most logic gates are made from MOSFETs (metal–oxide–semiconductor field-effect transistors).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] They can also be constructed using vacuum tubes, electromagnetic relays with relay logic, fluidic logic, pneumatic logic, optics, molecules, acoustics, or even mechanical or thermal elements.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Logic gates can be cascaded in the same way that Boolean functions can be composed, allowing the construction of a physical model of all of Boolean logic, and therefore, all of the algorithms and mathematics that can be described with Boolean logic.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] **Logic circuits** include such devices as multiplexers, registers, arithmetic logic units (ALUs), and computer memory, all the way up through complete microprocessors, which may contain more than 100 million logic gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Compound logic gates AND-OR-invert (AOI) and OR-AND-invert (OAI) are often employed in circuit design because their construction using MOSFETs is simpler and more efficient than the sum of the individual gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] There are seven basic logic gates: NOT, OR, NOR (Negation of the OR statement), AND, NAND (Negation of the AND statement), XOR (Exclusive OR), XNOR (Negation of the Exclusive OR statement).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The binary number system was refined by Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz (published in 1705), influenced by the ancient *I Ching*'s binary system.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Leibniz established that using the binary system combined the principles of arithmetic and logic.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The analytical engine devised by Charles Babbage in 1837 used mechanical logic gates based on gears.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In an 1886 letter, Charles Sanders Peirce described how logical operations could be carried out by electrical switching circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Early Electromechanical computers were constructed from switches and relay logic rather than the later innovations of vacuum tubes (thermionic valves) or transistors (from which later electronic computers were constructed).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Ludwig Wittgenstein introduced a version of the 16-row truth table as proposition 5.101 of *Tractatus Logico-Philosophicus* (1921).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Walther Bothe, inventor of the coincidence circuit, got part of the 1954 Nobel Prize in physics, for the first modern electronic AND gate in 1924.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Konrad Zuse designed and built electromechanical logic gates for his computer Z1 (from 1935 to 1938).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] From 1934 to 1936, NEC engineer Akira Nakashima, Claude Shannon and Victor Shestakov introduced switching circuit theory in a series of papers showing that two-valued Boolean algebra, which they discovered independently, can describe the operation of switching circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Using this property of electrical switches to implement logic is the fundamental concept that underlies all electronic digital computers.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Switching circuit theory became the foundation of digital circuit design, as it became widely known in the electrical engineering community during and after World War II, with theoretical rigor superseding the *ad hoc* methods that had prevailed previously.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In 1948, Bardeen and Brattain patented an insulated-gate transistor (IGFET) with an inversion layer.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Their concept forms the basis of CMOS technology today.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In 1957, Frosch and Derick were able to manufacture PMOS and NMOS planar gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Later a team at Bell Labs demonstrated a working MOS with PMOS and NMOS gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Both types were later combined and adapted into complementary MOS (CMOS) logic by Chih-Tang Sah and Frank Wanlass at Fairchild Semiconductor in 1963.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] There are two sets of symbols for elementary logic gates in common use, both defined in ANSI/IEEE Std 91-1984 and its supplement ANSI/IEEE Std 91a-1991.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The "distinctive shape" set, based on traditional schematics, is used for simple drawings and derives from United States Military Standard MIL-STD-806 of the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] It is sometimes unofficially described as "military", reflecting its origin.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The "rectangular shape" set, based on ANSI Y32.14 and other early industry standards as later refined by IEEE and IEC, has rectangular outlines for all types of gate and allows representation of a much wider range of devices than is possible with the traditional symbols.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The mutual goal of IEEE Std 91-1984 and IEC 617-12 was to provide a uniform method of describing the complex logic functions of digital circuits with schematic symbols.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] These functions were more complex than simple AND and OR gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] They could be medium-scale circuits such as a 4-bit counter to a large-scale circuit such as a microprocessor.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] IEC 617-12 and its renumbered successor IEC 60617-12 do not explicitly show the "distinctive shape" symbols, but do not prohibit them.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Usage of these other symbols in combination to form complex symbols (for example, use as embedded symbols) is discouraged." This compromise was reached between the respective IEEE and IEC working groups to permit the IEEE and IEC standards to be in mutual compliance with one another.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In the 1980s, schematics were the predominant method to design both circuit boards and custom ICs known as gate arrays.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Today custom ICs and the field-programmable gate array are typically designed with Hardware Description Languages (HDL) such as Verilog or VHDL.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] By use of De Morgan's laws, an *AND* function is identical to an *OR* function with negated inputs and outputs.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Likewise, an *OR* function is identical to an *AND* function with negated inputs and outputs.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A NAND gate is equivalent to an OR gate with negated inputs, and a NOR gate is equivalent to an AND gate with negated inputs.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] This leads to an alternative set of symbols for basic gates that use the opposite core symbol (*AND* or *OR*) but with the inputs and outputs negated.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Use of these alternative symbols can make logic circuit diagrams much clearer and help to show accidental connection of an active high output to an active low input or vice versa.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Any connection that has logic negations at both ends can be replaced by a negationless connection and a suitable change of gate or vice versa.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Any connection that has a negation at one end and no negation at the other can be made easier to interpret by instead using the De Morgan equivalent symbol at either of the two ends.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] When negation or polarity indicators on both ends of a connection match, there is no logic negation in that path (effectively, bubbles "cancel"), making it easier to follow logic states from one symbol to the next.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] This is commonly seen in real logic diagrams – thus the reader must not get into the habit of associating the shapes exclusively as OR or AND shapes, but also take into account the bubbles at both inputs and outputs in order to determine the "true" logic function indicated.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A De Morgan symbol can show more clearly a gate's primary logical purpose and the polarity of its nodes that are considered in the "signaled" (active, on) state.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Consider the simplified case where a two-input NAND gate is used to drive a motor when either of its inputs are brought low by a switch.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The "signaled" state (motor on) occurs when either one OR the other switch is on.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Unlike a regular NAND symbol, which suggests AND logic, the De Morgan version, a two negative-input OR gate, correctly shows that OR is of interest.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The regular NAND symbol has a bubble at the output and none at the inputs (the opposite of the states that will turn the motor on), but the De Morgan symbol shows both inputs and output in the polarity that will drive the motor.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] De Morgan's theorem is most commonly used to implement logic gates as combinations of only NAND gates, or as combinations of only NOR gates, for economic reasons.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Charles Sanders Peirce (during 1880–1881) showed that NOR gates alone (or alternatively NAND gates alone) can be used to reproduce the functions of all the other logic gates, but his work on it was unpublished until 1933.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The first published proof was by Henry M.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Sheffer in 1913, so the NAND logical operation is sometimes called *Sheffer stroke*; the logical NOR is sometimes called *Peirce's arrow*.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Consequently, these gates are sometimes called *universal logic gates*.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Logic gates can also be used to hold a state, allowing data storage.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A storage element can be constructed by connecting several gates in a "latch" circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Latching circuitry is used in static random-access memory.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] More complicated designs that use clock signals and that change only on a rising or falling edge of the clock are called edge-triggered "flip-flops".
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Formally, a flip-flop is called a bistable circuit, because it has two stable states which it can maintain indefinitely.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The combination of multiple flip-flops in parallel, used to store a multiple-bit value, is known as a register.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] When using any of these gate setups the overall system has memory; it is then called a sequential logic system since its output can be influenced by its previous state(s), i.e. by the *sequence* of input states.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In contrast, the output from combinational logic is purely a combination of its present inputs, unaffected by the previous input and output states.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] These logic circuits are used in computer memory.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] They vary in performance, based on factors of speed, complexity, and reliability of storage, and many different types of designs are used based on the application.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A functionally complete logic system may be composed of relays, valves (vacuum tubes), or transistors.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Electronic logic gates differ significantly from their relay-and-switch equivalents.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] They are much faster, consume much less power, and are much smaller (all by a factor of a million or more in most cases).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Also, there is a fundamental structural difference.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The switch circuit creates a continuous metallic path for current to flow (in either direction) between its input and its output.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The semiconductor logic gate, on the other hand, acts as a high-gain voltage amplifier, which sinks a tiny current at its input and produces a low-impedance voltage at its output.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] It is not possible for current to flow between the output and the input of a semiconductor logic gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] For small-scale logic, designers now use prefabricated logic gates from families of devices such as the TTL 7400 series by Texas Instruments, the CMOS 4000 series by RCA, and their more recent descendants.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Increasingly, these fixed-function logic gates are being replaced by programmable logic devices, which allow designers to pack many mixed logic gates into a single integrated circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] An important advantage of standardized integrated circuit logic families, such as the 7400 and 4000 families, is that they can be cascaded.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] This means that the output of one gate can be wired to the inputs of one or several other gates, and so on.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Systems with varying degrees of complexity can be built without great concern of the designer for the internal workings of the gates, provided the limitations of each integrated circuit are considered.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The output of one gate can only drive a finite number of inputs to other gates, a number called the "fan-out limit".
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Also, there is always a delay, called the "propagation delay", from a change in input of a gate to the corresponding change in its output.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] When gates are cascaded, the total propagation delay is approximately the sum of the individual delays, an effect which can become a problem in high-speed synchronous circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Additional delay can be caused when many inputs are connected to an output, due to the distributed capacitance of all the inputs and wiring and the finite amount of current that each output can provide.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] There are several logic families with different characteristics (power consumption, speed, cost, size) such as: RDL (resistor–diode logic), RTL (resistor–transistor logic), DTL (diode–transistor logic), TTL (transistor–transistor logic) and CMOS.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] There are also sub-variants, e.g. standard CMOS logic vs. advanced types using still CMOS technology, but with some optimizations for avoiding loss of speed due to slower PMOS transistors.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The simplest family of logic gates uses bipolar transistors, and is called resistor–transistor logic (RTL).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Unlike simple diode logic gates (which do not have a gain element), RTL gates can be cascaded indefinitely to produce more complex logic functions.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] RTL gates were used in early integrated circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] For higher speed and better density, the resistors used in RTL were replaced by diodes resulting in diode–transistor logic (DTL).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Transistor–transistor logic (TTL) then supplanted DTL.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] As integrated circuits became more complex, bipolar transistors were replaced with smaller field-effect transistors (MOSFETs); see PMOS and NMOS.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] To reduce power consumption still further, most contemporary chip implementations of digital systems now use CMOS logic.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] CMOS uses complementary (both n-channel and p-channel) MOSFET devices to achieve a high speed with low power dissipation.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A three-state logic gate is a type of logic gate that can have three different outputs: high (H), low (L) and high-impedance (Z).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] The high-impedance state plays no role in the logic, which is strictly binary.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] These devices are used on buses of the CPU to allow multiple chips to send data.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A group of three-state outputs driving a line with a suitable control circuit is basically equivalent to a multiplexer, which may be physically distributed over separate devices or plug-in cards.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In electronics, a high output would mean the output is sourcing current from the positive power terminal (positive voltage).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] A low output would mean the output is sinking current to the negative power terminal (zero voltage).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] High impedance would mean that the output is effectively disconnected from the circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Non-electronic implementations are varied, though few of them are used in practical applications.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Many early electromechanical digital computers, such as the Harvard Mark I, were built from relay logic gates, using electro-mechanical relays.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Logic gates can be made using pneumatic devices, such as the Sorteberg relay or mechanical logic gates, including on a molecular scale.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Various types of fundamental logic gates have been constructed using molecules (molecular logic gates), which are based on chemical inputs and spectroscopic outputs.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Logic gates have been made out of DNA (see DNA nanotechnology) and used to create a computer called MAYA (see MAYA-II).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Logic gates can be made from quantum mechanical effects, see quantum logic gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Photonic logic gates use nonlinear optical effects.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] In principle any method that leads to a gate that is functionally complete (for example, either a NOR or a NAND gate) can be used to make any kind of digital logic circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-gate] Note that the use of 3-state logic for bus systems is not needed, and can be replaced by digital multiplexers, which can be built using only simple logic gates (such as NAND gates, NOR gates, or AND and OR gates).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] In computer engineering, **logic synthesis** is a process by which an abstract specification of desired circuit behavior, typically at register transfer level (RTL), is turned into a design implementation in terms of logic gates, typically by a computer program called a *synthesis tool*.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Common examples of this process include synthesis of designs specified in hardware description languages, including VHDL and Verilog.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Some synthesis tools generate bitstreams for programmable logic devices such as PALs or FPGAs, while others target the creation of ASICs.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Logic synthesis is one step in circuit design in the electronic design automation, the others are place and route and verification and validation.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The roots of logic synthesis can be traced to the treatment of logic by George Boole (1815 to 1864), in what is now termed Boolean algebra.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] In 1938, Claude Shannon showed that the two-valued Boolean algebra can describe the operation of switching circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] In the early days, **logic design** involved manipulating the truth table representations as Karnaugh maps.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The Karnaugh map-based minimization of logic is guided by a set of rules on how entries in the maps can be combined.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] A human designer can typically only work with Karnaugh maps containing up to four to six variables.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The first step toward automation of logic minimization was the introduction of the Quine–McCluskey algorithm that could be implemented on a computer.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] This exact minimization technique presented the notion of prime implicants and minimum cost covers that would become the cornerstone of two-level minimization.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Nowadays, the much more efficient Espresso heuristic logic minimizer has become the standard tool for this operation.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Another area of early research was in state minimization and encoding of finite-state machines (FSMs), a task that was the bane of designers.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The applications for logic synthesis lay primarily in digital computer design.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Hence, IBM and Bell Labs played a pivotal role in the early automation of logic synthesis.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The evolution from discrete logic components to programmable logic arrays (PLAs) hastened the need for efficient two-level minimization, since minimizing terms in a two-level representation reduces the area in a PLA.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Two-level logic circuits are of limited importance in a very-large-scale integration (VLSI) design; most designs use multiple levels of logic.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Almost any circuit representation in RTL or Behavioural Description is a multi-level representation.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] An early system that was used to design multilevel circuits was LSS from IBM.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] It used local transformations to simplify logic.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Work on LSS and the Yorktown Silicon Compiler spurred rapid research progress in logic synthesis in the 1980s.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Several universities contributed by making their research available to the public, most notably SIS from University of California, Berkeley, RASP from University of California, Los Angeles and BOLD from University of Colorado, Boulder.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Within a decade, the technology migrated to commercial logic synthesis products offered by electronic design automation companies.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The leading developers and providers of logic synthesis software packages are Synopsys, Cadence, and Siemens.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Their synthesis tools are Synopsys Design Compiler, Cadence First Encounter and Siemens Precision RTL.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Logic operations usually consist of Boolean AND, OR, XOR and NAND operations, and are the most basic forms of operations in an electronic circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Arithmetic operations are usually implemented with the use of logic operators.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] With a goal of increasing designer productivity, research efforts on the synthesis of circuits specified at the behavioral level have led to the emergence of commercial solutions in 2004, which are used for complex ASIC and FPGA design.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] These tools automatically synthesize circuits specified using high-level languages, like ANSI C/C++ or SystemC, to a register transfer level (RTL) specification, which can be used as input to a gate-level logic synthesis flow.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Typical practical implementations of a logic function utilize a multi-level network of logic elements.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Starting from an RTL description of a design, the synthesis tool constructs a corresponding multilevel Boolean network.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Next, this network is optimized using several technology-independent techniques before technology-dependent optimizations are performed.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The typical cost function during technology-independent optimizations is total literal count of the factored representation of the logic function (which correlates quite well with circuit area).
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Finally, technology-dependent optimization transforms the technology-independent circuit into a network of gates in a given technology.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] The simple cost estimates are replaced by more concrete, implementation-driven estimates during and after technology mapping.
[src:standard-cell-library/logic-synthesis] Mapping is constrained by factors such as the available gates (logic functions) in the technology library, the drive sizes for each gate, and the delay, power, and area characteristics of each gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] In digital electronics, a **NAND** (**NOT AND**) **gate** is a logic gate which produces an output which is false only if all its inputs are true; thus its output is complement to that of an AND gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] A LOW (0) output results only if all the inputs to the gate are HIGH (1); if any input is LOW (0), a HIGH (1) output results.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] A NAND gate is made using transistors and junction diodes.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] By De Morgan's laws, a two-input NAND gate's logic may be expressed as ${\overline {A}}\lor {\overline {B}}={\overline {A\cdot B}}$ , making a NAND gate equivalent to inverters followed by an OR gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] The NAND gate is significant because any Boolean function can be implemented by using a combination of NAND gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] This property is called "functional completeness".
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] It shares this property with the NOR gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] Digital systems employing certain logic circuits take advantage of NAND's functional completeness.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] NAND gates with two or more inputs are available as integrated circuits in transistor–transistor logic, CMOS, and other logic families.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] There are three symbols for NAND gates: the *MIL/ANSI* symbol, the *IEC* symbol and the deprecated *DIN* symbol sometimes found on old schematics.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] The ANSI symbol for the NAND gate is a standard AND gate with an inversion bubble connected.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] The function NAND(*a*1, *a*2, ..., *an*) is logically equivalent to NOT(*a*1 AND *a*2 AND ...
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] One way of expressing A NAND B is ${\overline {A\land B}}$ , where the symbol ${\land }$ signifies AND and the bar signifies the negation of the expression under it: in essence, simply ${\displaystyle \lnot (A\land B)}$ .
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] The basic implementations can be understood from the image on the left below: If either of the switches S1 or S2 is open, the pull-up resistor R will set the output signal Q to 1 (high).
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] If S1 and S2 are both closed, the pull-up resistor will be overridden by the switches, and the output will be 0 (low).
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] In the depletion-load NMOS logic realization in the middle below, the switches are the transistors T2 and T3, and the transistor T1 fulfills the function of the pull-up resistor.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] In the CMOS realization on the right below, the switches are the n-type transistors T3 and T4, and the pull-up resistor is made up of the p-type transistors T1 and T2, which form the complement of transistors T3 and T4.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] In CMOS, NAND gates are more efficient than NOR gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] This is due to the faster charge mobility in n-MOSFETs compared to p-MOSFETs, so that the parallel connection of two p-MOSFETs (T1 and T2) realised in the NAND gate is more favourable than their series connection in the NOR gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] For this reason, NAND gates are generally preferred over NOR gates in CMOS circuits.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] NAND gates are basic logic gates, and as such they are recognised in TTL and CMOS ICs.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] The standard, 4000 series, CMOS IC is the 4011, which includes four independent, two-input, NAND gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] These devices are available from many semiconductor manufacturers.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] These are usually available in both through-hole DIL and SOIC formats.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] Datasheets are readily available in most datasheet databases.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] The NAND gate has the property of functional completeness, which it shares with the NOR gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] That is, any other logic function (AND, OR, etc.) can be implemented using only NAND gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] An entire processor can be created using NAND gates alone.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] In TTL ICs using multiple-emitter transistors, it also requires fewer transistors than a NOR gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/nand-gate] As NOR gates are also functionally complete, if no specific NAND gates are available, one can be made from NOR gates using NOR logic.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In electronic design, a **netlist** is a description of the connectivity of an electronic circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In its simplest form, a netlist consists of a list of the electronic components in a circuit and a list of the nodes they are connected to.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] A network (net) is a collection of two or more interconnected components.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] The structure, complexity and representation of netlists can vary considerably, but the fundamental purpose of every netlist is to convey connectivity information.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Netlists usually provide nothing more than instances, nodes, and perhaps some attributes of the components involved.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] If they express much more than this, they are usually considered to be a hardware description language such as Verilog or VHDL, or one of several languages specifically designed for input to simulators or hardware compilers (such as SPICE analog simulation netlists).
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Most netlists either contain or refer to descriptions of the parts or devices used.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Each time a part is used in a netlist, this is called an "instance".
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] These descriptions will usually list the connections that are made to that kind of device, and some basic properties of that device.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] These connection points are called "terminals" or "pins", among several other names.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] An "instance" could be anything from a MOSFET transistor or a bipolar junction transistor, to a resistor, a capacitor, or an integrated circuit chip.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In the case of a vacuum cleaner, these terminals would be the three metal prongs in the plug.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Each terminal has a name, and in continuing the vacuum cleaner example, they might be "Neutral", "Live" and "Ground".
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Usually, each instance will have a unique name, so that if you have two instances of vacuum cleaners, one might be "vac1" and the other "vac2".
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Besides their names, they might otherwise be identical.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Networks (nets) are the "wires" that connect things together in the circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] There may or may not be any special attributes associated with the nets in a design, depending on the particular language the netlist is written in, and that language's features.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Instance based netlists usually provide a list of the instances used in a design.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Along with each instance, either an ordered list of net names is provided, or a list of pairs provided, of an instance port name, along with the net name to which that port is connected.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In this kind of description, the list of nets can be gathered from the connection lists, and there is no place to associate particular attributes with the nets themselves.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] SPICE is an example of instance-based netlists.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Net-based netlists usually describe all the instances and their attributes, then describe each net, and say which port they are connected on each instance.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] This allows for attributes to be associated with nets.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] EDIF is probably the most famous of the net-based netlists.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In large designs, it is a common practice to split the design into pieces, each piece becoming a "definition" which can be used as instances in the design.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In the vacuum cleaner analogy, one might have a vacuum cleaner definition with its ports, but now this definition would also include a full description of the machine's internal components and how they connect (motors, switches, etc.), like a wiring diagram does.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] A definition which includes no instances is called a "primitive" (or a "leaf", or other names); whereas a definition which includes instances is "hierarchical".
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] A "folded" hierarchy allows a single definition to be represented several times by instances.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] An "unfolded" hierarchy does not allow a definition to be used more than once in the hierarchy.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Folded hierarchies can be extremely compact.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] A small netlist of just a few instances can describe designs with a very large number of instances.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] For example, suppose definition A is a simple primitive, like a memory cell.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Then suppose definition B contains 32 instances of A; C contains 32 instances of B; D contains 32 instances of C; and E contains 32 instances of D.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] The design now contains 5 definitions (A through E) and 128 instances.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Yet, E describes a circuit that contains over a million memory cells.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In a "flat" design, only primitives are instanced.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Hierarchical designs can be recursively "exploded" ("flattened") by creating a new copy (with a new name) of each definition each time it is used.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] If the design is highly folded, expanding it like this will result in a much larger netlist database, but preserves the hierarchy dependencies.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Given a hierarchical netlist, the list of instance names in a path from the root definition to a primitive instance specifies the single unique path to that primitive.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] The paths to every primitive, taken together, comprise a large but flat netlist that is exactly equivalent to the compact hierarchical version.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Backannotation is data that could be added to a hierarchical netlist.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Usually they are kept separate from the netlist, because several such alternate sets of data could be applied to a single netlist.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] These data may have been extracted from a physical design, and might provide extra information for more accurate simulations.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Usually the data are composed of a hierarchical path and a piece of data for that primitive or finding the values of RC delay due to interconnection.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Another concept often used in netlists is that of inheritance.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Suppose a definition of a capacitor has an associated attribute called "Capacitance", corresponding to the physical property of the same name, with a default value of "100 pF" (100 picofarads).
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] Each instance of this capacitor might also have such an attribute, only with a different value of capacitance.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] And other instances might not associate any capacitance at all.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] In the case where no capacitance is specified for an instance, the instance will "inherit" the 100 pF value from its definition.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] A value specified will "override" the value on the definition.
[src:standard-cell-library/netlist] If a great number of attributes end up being the same as on the definition, a great amount of information can be "inherited", and not have to be redundantly specified in the netlist, saving space, and making the design easier to read by both machines and people.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] In semiconductor design, **standard-cell methodology** is a method of designing application-specific integrated circuits (ASICs) with mostly digital-logic features.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Standard-cell methodology is an example of design abstraction, whereby a low-level very-large-scale integration (VLSI) layout is encapsulated into an abstract logic representation (such as a NAND gate).
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Cell-based methodology – the general class to which standard cells belong – makes it possible for one designer to focus on the high-level (logical function) aspect of digital design, while another designer focuses on the implementation (physical) aspect.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Along with semiconductor manufacturing advances, standard-cell methodology has helped designers scale ASICs from comparatively simple single-function ICs (of several thousand gates), to complex multi-million gate system-on-a-chip (SoC) devices.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A standard cell is a group of transistor and interconnect structures that provides a Boolean logic function (e.g., AND, OR, XOR, XNOR, inverters) or a storage function (flipflop or latch).
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Usually, the initial design of a standard cell is developed at the transistor level, in the form of a *transistor netlist* or *schematic* view.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The netlist is a nodal description of transistors, of their connections to each other, and of their terminals (ports) to the external environment.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A schematic view may be generated with a number of different computer-aided design (CAD) or electronic design automation (EDA) programs that provide a graphical user interface (GUI) for this netlist generation process.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Designers use additional CAD programs such as SPICE to simulate the electronic behavior of the netlist, by declaring input stimulus (voltage or current waveforms) and then calculating the circuit's time domain (analog) response.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The simulations verify whether the netlist implements the desired function and predict other pertinent parameters, such as power consumption or signal propagation delay.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Since the logical and netlist views are only useful for abstract (algebraic) simulation, and not device fabrication, the physical representation of the standard cell must be designed too.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Also called the *layout view*, this is the lowest level of design abstraction in common design practice.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] From a manufacturing perspective, the standard cell's VLSI layout is the most important view, as it is closest to an actual "manufacturing blueprint" of the standard cell.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The layout is organized into *base layers*, which correspond to the different structures of the transistor devices, and *interconnect wiring layers* and *via layers*, which join together the terminals of the transistor formations.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The *interconnect wiring layers* are usually numbered and have specific *via* layers representing specific connections between each sequential layer.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Non-manufacturing layers may also be present in a layout for purposes of design automation, but many layers used explicitly for place and route (PNR) CAD programs are often included in a separate but similar *abstract* view.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The abstract view often contains much less information than the layout and may be recognizable as a Library Exchange Format (LEF) file or an equivalent.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] After a layout is created, additional CAD tools are often used to perform a number of common validations.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A design rule check (DRC) is done to verify that the design meets foundry and other layout requirements.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A parasitic extraction (PEX) then is performed to generate a PEX-netlist with parasitic properties from the layout.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The nodal connections of that netlist are then compared to those of the schematic netlist with a *layout vs schematic* (LVS) procedure to verify that the connectivity models are equivalent.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The PEX-netlist may then be simulated again (since it contains parasitic properties) to achieve more accurate timing, power, and noise models.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] These models are often *characterized* (contained) in a Synopsys Liberty format, but other Verilog formats may be used as well.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Finally, powerful place and route (PNR) tools may be used to pull everything together and *synthesize* (generate) very-large-scale integration (VLSI) layouts, in an automated fashion, from higher level design netlists and floor-plans.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Additionally, a number of other CAD tools may be used to validate other aspects of the cell views and models.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] And other files may be created to support various tools that utilize the standard cells for a plethora of other reasons.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] All of these files that are created to support the use of all of the standard-cell variations are collectively known as a standard-cell library.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] For a typical Boolean function, there are many different functionally equivalent transistor netlists.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Likewise, for a typical netlist, there are many different layouts that fit the netlist's performance parameters.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The designer's challenge is to minimize the manufacturing cost of the standard cell's layout (generally by minimizing the circuit's die area), while still meeting the cell's speed and power performance requirements.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Consequently, integrated circuit layout is a highly labor-intensive job, despite the existence of design tools to aid this process.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A standard-cell library is a collection of low-level electronic logic functions such as AND, OR, NOT, flip-flops, latches, and buffers.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] These cells are realized as fixed-height, variable-width full-custom cells.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The key aspect with these libraries is that they are of a fixed height, which enables them to be placed in rows, easing the process of automated digital layout.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The cells are typically optimized full-custom layouts, which minimize delays and area.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Timing abstract - generally in Liberty format, to provide functional definitions, timing, power, and noise information for each cell.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] An example is a simple XOR logic gate, which can be formed from OR, NOT and AND gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Strictly speaking, a 2-input NAND or NOR function is sufficient to form any arbitrary Boolean function set.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] But in modern ASIC design, standard-cell methodology is practiced with a sizable library (or libraries) of cells.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The library usually contains multiple implementations of the same logic function, differing in area and speed.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] This variety enhances the efficiency of automated synthesis, place, and route (SPR) tools.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Indirectly, it also gives the designer greater freedom to perform implementation trade-offs (area vs. speed vs. power consumption).
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A complete group of standard-cell descriptions is commonly called a *technology library*.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Commercially available electronic design automation (EDA) tools use the technology libraries to automate synthesis, placement, and routing of a digital ASIC.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The technology library is developed and distributed by the foundry operator.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The library (along with a design netlist format) is the basis for exchanging design information between different phases of the SPR process.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Using the technology library's cell logical view, the logic synthesis tool performs the process of mathematically transforming the ASIC's register-transfer level (RTL) description into a technology-dependent netlist.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] This process is analogous to a software compiler converting a high-level C-program listing into a processor-dependent assembly-language listing.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The netlist is the standard-cell representation of the ASIC design, at the logical view level.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] It consists of instances of the standard-cell library gates, and port connectivity between gates.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Proper synthesis techniques ensure mathematical equivalency between the synthesized netlist and original RTL description.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The netlist contains no unmapped RTL statements and declarations.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The high-level synthesis tool performs the process of transforming the C-level models (SystemC, ANSI C/C++) description into a technology-dependent netlist.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The placement tool starts the physical implementation of the ASIC.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] With a 2-D floorplan provided by the ASIC designer, the placer tool assigns locations for each gate in the netlist.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The resulting *placed gates* netlist contains the physical location of each of the netlist's standard-cells, but retains an abstract description of how the gates' terminals are wired to each other.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Typically the standard cells have a constant size in at least one dimension that allows them to be lined up in rows on the integrated circuit.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The chip will consist of a huge number of rows (with power and ground running next to each row) with each row filled with the various cells making up the actual design.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Placers obey certain rules: Each gate is assigned a unique (exclusive) location on the die map.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] A given gate is placed once, and may not occupy or overlap the location of any other gate.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Using the placed-gates netlist and the layout view of the library, the router adds both signal connect lines and power supply lines.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The fully routed physical netlist contains the listing of gates from synthesis, the placement of each gate from placement, and the drawn interconnects from routing.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Design rule check (DRC) and layout versus schematic (LVS) are verification processes.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Reliable device fabrication at modern deep-submicrometer (0.13 μm and below) requires strict observance of transistor spacing, metal layer thickness, and power density rules.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] DRC exhaustively compares the physical netlist against a set of "foundry design rules" (from the foundry operator), then flags any observed violations.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The LVS process confirms that the layout has the same structure as the associated schematic; this is typically the final step in the layout process.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The LVS tool takes as an input a schematic diagram and the extracted view from a layout.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] It then generates a netlist from each one and compares them.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Nodes, ports, and device sizing are all compared.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] If they are the same, LVS passes and the designer can continue.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] LVS tends to consider transistor fingers to be the same as an extra-wide transistor.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Thus, 4 transistors (each 1 μm wide) in parallel, a 4-finger 1 μm transistor, or a 4 μm transistor are viewed the same by the LVS tool.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The functionality of .lib files will be taken from SPICE models and added as an attribute to the .lib file.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] In semiconductor design, standard cells are ensured to be design rule checking (DRC) and layout versus schematic (LVS) compliant.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] This compliance significantly enhances the efficiency of the design process, leading to reduced turnaround times for designers.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] By ensuring that these cells meet critical verification standards, designers can streamline the integration of these components into larger chip designs, facilitating a smoother and faster development cycle.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] "Standard cell" falls into a more general class of design automation flows called cell-based design.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] Structured ASICs, FPGAs, and CPLDs are variations on cell-based design.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] From the designer's standpoint, all share the same input front end: an RTL description of the design.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] The three techniques, however, differ substantially in the details of the SPR flow (synthesize, place-and-route) and physical implementation.
[src:standard-cell-library/standard-cell] For digital standard-cell designs, for instance in CMOS, a common technology-independent metric for complexity measure is gate equivalents (GE).
